	State in 1-2 paragraphs how you would control for quality.  What measurements would you take in order to make a case that this project was of high quality?
	 
	List the risks involved in doing this project at each step.  Accompany each with a statement about how you would mitigate risk.

Assigning project manager
Risk - Not all team members agreeing on who the project manager will be
Mitigation - Perform team building activities that will build trust among the members
Identify key stakeholders
Risk - Uncertainty of who the key stakeholders are
Mitigation - Perform background research and identify key stakeholders of similar projects
Prepare business case
Risk - Uncertainty in strength of business case
Mitigation - Study similar successful business cases
Prepare project charter
Risk - Unclear what the roles and responsibilities are
Mitigation - Have a team meeting to iron this out
Hold project kickoff meeting
Risk - Lack of stakeholder buy-in
Mitigation - Plan kickoff meeting that best encourages stakeholder buy-in
Prepare team contract
Risk - Disagreement among members about contents of contract
Mitigation - Survey members about their priorities for the team
Prepare scope statement
Risk - Scope Creep
Mitigation - Regular meetings to verify scope against requirements
Prepare WBS
Risk - Uncertainty of what tasks needed to be done
Mitigation - Consult with experts or people who worked on similar projects

Determine task resources
Risk - Lack of overall resources
Mitigation - Make do with what we have or take the time to pull together the necessary resources
Determine task durations
Risk - Unrealistic durations
Mitigation - Consult with experts or people who worked on similar projects
Determine task dependencies
Risk - External/Third Party dependents not following through (e.g. supplier, investor)
Mitigation - Have multiple dependencies so that the project is not reliant on individual dependents
Create draft Gantt chart
Risk - Technology failure/breakdown (e.g. software/hardware crashes)
Mitigation - Have physical paper draft on hand and prepared
Review and finalize Gantt chart
Risk - Disagreement on final aspects of Gantt chart among members
Mitigation - Conduct several review sessions before final review session
Identify, discuss, and prioritize risks
Risk - Unknown risks
Mitigation - Consult with experts or people who worked on similar projects
List pros/cons of existing applications
Risk - Finding the market is saturated with successful products
Mitigation - Use this as an opportunity to think about the unique contribution our project will make
User Inputs
Risk - No user involvement
Mitigation - Be ready to spend money on alternative user input sources
Interviews
Risk - Inconclusive data from interviews
Mitigation - Perform research to determine the right questions to ask
Surveys
Risk - Conflicting answers to surveys
Mitigation - Narrow the audience to target specific groups of users
Copyrights, patent encroachment, considerations
Cost - $35 (source: US Patent Office)
Risk - Overlooked considerations
Mitigation - Pay a good lawyer so that nothing is overlooked

Mitigation - Be willing to spend good money for good legal advice
Third-party API access
Risk - No third-party or stakeholder support
Mitigation - Continually market to third parties on benefits to their bottom line if allowing our project access
Hire development team
Cost - $420,000 (4 * $70,000/yr + (4* $35,000))
Risk - Underestimating cost
Mitigation - Overestimate it or set up salary contract that is legally binding
Register developer iOS devices
Cost - $99
Risk - New, upgraded devices hit the market in the middle of the project
Mitigation - Plan to develop project as universally as possible
Secure access to Retailer databases
Risk - No retailer support
Mitigation - Start with our own built database or continually market to retailers on benefits to their bottom line if allowing our project access
Secure access to public weather databases
Risk - Inaccurate sources
Mitigation - Find reliable sources and multiple sources
Create mock-ups/prototypes
Risk - Creating a polished mock-up and getting locked into that design
Mitigation - Implement paper prototyping with a “fail fast” approach
Internal testing on developer devices
Risk - Incomplete or biased testing
Mitigation - Continually verify tests against requirements
Closed beta testing to select members
Risk - Minimal to no results from beta testing
Mitigation - Prepare to spend money on longitudinal beta test
Refine/iterate development
Risk - Never-ending refinement/iteration
Mitigation - Continually refer to requirements and consult with stakeholders
Social media promotion of app
Risk - Negative social feedback during promotion
Mitigation - Use that as opportunity to find areas of improvement in our project
App roll-out
Risk - Little to no app adoption upon roll-out
Mitigation - Make sure to employ aggressive marketing and promotion prior to roll-out
Project benefits measurement
Risk - Inaccurate measurements
Mitigation - Consult with expert or people who worked on similar projects
Daily meetings
Risk - Conflicting schedule
Mitigation - Set calendar priorities
Status reports
Risk - No member input
Mitigation - Revisit team contract and re-establish buy-in to publish reports regularly and on time
Debugging/QA
Risk - Unrealistic expectations of quality goals
Mitigation - Refer to requirements and continually meet with stakeholders
Prepare final project report
Risk - Temptation of non-disclosure
Mitigation - Establish early on transparent lines of communication among team and stakeholders
Prepare final project presentation
Risk - Nervous members anxious about presenting (especially to investors)
Mitigation - Practice, practice, practice
Lessons Learned
Risk - Temptation to discouragement from focusing on negative aspects
Mitigation - Celebrate victories as a team
